{{coord|51.708|-4.989|display=title|region:GB_scale:10000}}
The '''Esso Refinery''' at [[Milford Haven]] was an [[oil refinery]] situated on the Pembrokeshire coast in [[Wales]]. Construction started in 1957 and the refinery was opened in 1960 by the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]].<ref name="eugene">{{cite news |title=Refinery Opens |work=Eugene Register-Guard |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rXQRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7eIDAAAAIBAJ&dq=esso%20milford&pg=3252%2C473132 |date=1960-12-04}}</ref> Construction cost £18million and the refinery had the capacity to process 4.5million tons of crude oil a year.<ref name="eugene"/>

The refinery closed down in March 1983.<ref>{{cite book |p=74 |title=The quest for productivity |first=Bruce W. |last=Ahlstrand |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-521-36380-8 |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref> Today, the site has been converted by the owners [[Exxonmobil]] into the [[South Hook LNG terminal]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Call for gas plant disaster plan |work=The Western Mail |date=2004-02-16 |last=Jones |first=Ceri}}</ref>

