{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}
'''Gin Drinkers Bay''' ({{zh|t=醉酒灣|l=Drunkard's Bay}}) or '''Gin Drinker's Bay''', also known as '''Lap Sap Wan''' ({{zh|t=垃圾灣|l=Rubbish Bay|j=laap6 saap3 waan1}}), was a [[bay]] in [[Kwai Chung]], [[Hong Kong]].

The bay was [[Land reclamation in Hong Kong|reclaimed]] in the 1960s and became [[Kwai Fong]] and part of [[Kwai Hing]]. At the mouth of the bay stood the island of [[Pillar Island]].

The bay was a [[harbour]] for [[Tanka (ethnic group)|Tanka]] fishing [[Junk (ship)|junks]]. They relocated to [[Tsing Yi Tong]] and [[Mun Tsai Tong]] of [[Tsing Yi Island]] before the commencement of reclamation.

''Lap Sap'' (垃圾) means "rubbish" in [[Cantonese]]. It is unclear why the bay was named "rubbish" in the past. However, it was coincidentally once a dumping area for rubbish after extensive reclamation.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bray|first1=Denis|title=Hong Kong Metamorphosis|date=2001|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|location=Aberdeen, Hong Kong|pages=80–81|accessdate=9 July 2014}}</ref> It is assumed that in [[Gin Drinkers Bay Park]] or [[Kwai Chung Park]] near Pillar Island that the area is subject to [[landfill gas]] produced deep in the ground even though it is covered with earthen hills. It remains closed due to unsafe levels of landfill gas.

Gin Drinkers Bay is known for the [[Gin Drinkers Line]], which formed a defensive line against the [[Battle of Hong Kong|Japanese invasion]] in 1941.

