{{for|the production company|Lacewood Productions}} '''Lacewood''' is a common name for the wood produced from a number of different trees, with mostly a striking appearance of their „[[lace]]-wood“, which gets its name from the lacelike pattern: These include: * ''[[Allanblackia floribunda]]'', ''[[Allanblackia parviflora]]'', west african trees * ''[[Cardwellia sublimis]]'', an australian tree * ''[[Elaeocarpus bojeri]]'', „bois dentelle“, due to the unique patterns of its flowers * ''[[Firmiana papuana]]'', a tree from New Guinea * ''[[Grevillea robusta]]'', an east australian tree * ''[[Lagetta lagetto]]'', an caribbean tree, [[lacebark tree]], lace tree, „bois dentelle“, the inner bark is formed of reticulated fibres so as to resemble a coarse kind of lace. * ''[[Monoon oblongifolium]]'' (Syn.: ''Polyalthia oblongifolia'') Mempisang, a philppinean tree, yellow lacewood * ''[[Platanus]]'' spp.; ''[[Platanus occidentalis]]'' American sycamore, [[Platanus × hispanica|''Platanus'' × ''hispanica'']] London plane <ref>{{cite book |last=Lincoln |first=William A |title=World Woods in Colour |year=1986 |publisher=Stobard Davies Ltd |location=Hertford UK |isbn=0-85442-028-2}}</ref> * ''[[Panopsis]]'' spp.; ''[[Panopsis rubescens]]'' and ''[[Panopsis sessilifolia]]'' <ref>[http://www.wood-database.com/lumber-identification/hardwoods/lacewood/ Wood databsase - Lacewood]</ref> * [[Roupala montana var. brasiliensis|''Roupala montana'' var. ''brasiliensis'']] Leopardwood, brazilian lacewood, south american lacewood, ropala lacewood * ''[[Sterculia shillinglawii]]''
