{{Infobox power station | name = Lucens reactor | image = Control room - Lucens reactor - 1968 - L17-0251-0105.jpg | image_caption = Control room of the Lucens reactor in April 1968 | location_map = Switzerland | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|46|41|34.16|N|6|49|36.81|E|type:landmark_region:CH-AG|display=inline,title}} | name_official = Versuchsatomkraftwerk Lucens | country = [[Switzerland]] | location = [[Lucens]], [[Vaud]] | status = D | construction_began = {{start date|1962|04|1|df=y}} | commissioned = {{start date|1968|05|10|df=y}} | decommissioned = {{start date|1969|03|03|df=y}} | cost = | owner = [[Nationale Gesellschaft zur Förderung der industriellen Atomtechnik]] | operator = [[Energie Ouest Suisse]] | ps_units_operational = | ps_units_uc = | ps_units_planned = | ps_units_decommissioned = 1 x 6&nbsp;MW<ref name="pris"/> | np_reactor_type = HWGCR | np_reactor_supplier = [[Thermatom]] | np_fuel_type = [[Low enriched uranium]] | np_cooling_source = [[Carbon dioxide]] | ps_electrical_capacity = 6 | ps_annual_generation = | website = {{URL|https://www.ensi.ch/fr/themes/centrale-nucleaire-lucens}} | extra = Suffered a nuclear accident on 21 January 1969, leading to a partial core meltdown and massive radioactive contamination }}
The '''Lucens reactor''' was a 6&nbsp;[[megawatt|MW]] experimental [[nuclear reactor|nuclear power reactor]] built next to [[Lucens]], [[Vaud]], Switzerland. After its connection to the electrical grid on 29 January 1968, the reactor only operated for a few months before it suffered a loss-of-coolant accident on 21 January 1969, leading to the meltdown of one of the five fuel elements <ref>J. Wolters: ''Aufgetretene Unfälle mit Kernschäden''; in ''Atomwirtschaft'', Juni 1987</ref> and radioactive contamination of the cavern.<ref name="pris" />
== Description == In 1962 the construction of a Swiss-designed [[pilot plant|pilot]] [[nuclear power plant]] began.<ref name="pris">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iaea.org/PRIS/CountryStatistics/ReactorDetails.aspx?current=966|title=LUCENS – Reactor Details|last=|first=|date=|website=IAEA Power Reactor Information System|publisher=[[International Atomic Energy Agency]]|access-date=2016-10-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxABBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|title=Sources of Information on Atomic Energy – International Series of Monographs in Library and Information Science|last=Anthony|first=L. J.|publisher=Elsevier|year=1966|isbn=978-1-4831-5600-2|series=|volume=2|location=|pages=85|language=en|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Wildi|first=Tobias|date=2003|title=Der Traum vom eigenen Reaktor – die schweizerische Atomtechnologieentwicklung 1945–1969|url=http://e-collection.library.ethz.ch/eserv/eth:30387/eth-30387-01.pdf|journal=PhD Dissertation|language=de|publisher=Chronos|volume=|doi=10.3929/ethz-a-004459704|isbn=978-3-0340-0594-4|hdl=20.500.11850/88080}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/f/F17356.php|title=Energie nucléaire|last=Hug|first=Peter|date=2009|website=[[Historical Dictionary of Switzerland|Dictionnaire historique de la Suisse]]|publisher=Gilles Attinger|location=Hauterive|language=fr|access-date=2016-10-09}}</ref> The [[heavy-water reactor|heavy-water]] moderated, [[carbon dioxide]] [[gas-cooled reactor types|gas-cooled]] reactor was built in an underground [[cave]]rn.<ref>[http://www.sapierr.net/files1/results_swiss.htm Summary of Swiss nuclear reactors], SAPIERR Support Action: Pilot Initiative for European Regional Repositories {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719140734/http://www.sapierr.net/files1/results_swiss.htm |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref> It produced 28&nbsp;MW of heat, which was used to generate 6&nbsp;MW of electricity, and it became critical 29 December 1966.<ref name="pris" /> It was fueled by 0.96% [[enriched uranium]] alloyed with [[chromium]] cased in [[magnesium]] alloy (magnesium with 0.6% [[zirconium]]) inserted into a [[nuclear graphite|graphite]] matrix. Carbon dioxide gas was pumped into the top of the channels at 6.28&nbsp;[[MPa]] and 223&nbsp;°C and exited the channels at a pressure of 5.79&nbsp;MPa and at a temperature of 378&nbsp;°C.<ref>{{cite book | last = | first = | title = Heavy water reactors : status and projected development | publisher = International Atomic Energy Agency | location = Vienna | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-9201115027|url=http://www-pub.iaea.org/MTCD/publications/PDF/TRS407_scr/D407_scr1.pdf }}</ref>
== Nuclear accident == {{Switzerland nuke plant map|float=right}}
It was intended to operate until the end of 1969, but during a startup on 21 January 1969, it suffered a [[loss-of-coolant accident]], leading to a partial core meltdown and the [[radioactive contamination]] of the cavern, which was then sealed.<ref>J. Wolters: ''Aufgetretene Unfälle mit Kernschäden''; in Atomwirtschaft, Juni 1987</ref> Using the criteria of the [[International Nuclear Event Scale]], introduced in 1990 by the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]], the event has been assessed as a Level 4 "Accident with local consequences".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ha-Duong|first=Minh|last2=Journé|first2=Venance|date=2014-05-14|title=Calculating nuclear accident probabilities from empirical frequencies|url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01018478/document|journal=Environment Systems and Decisions|language=en|volume=34|issue=2|pages=249–258|doi=10.1007/s10669-014-9499-0|issn=2194-5403}}</ref>
The accident was caused by water condensation forming on some of the magnesium alloy [[fuel element]] components during shutdown and corroding them. The [[corrosion]] products from this accumulated in some of the fuel channels. One of the vertical fuel channels was sufficiently blocked by it to impede the flow of carbon dioxide coolant so that the magnesium alloy cladding melted and further blocked the channel. The increase in temperature and exposure of the uranium metal fuel to the [[coolant]] eventually caused the fuel to catch fire in the carbon dioxide coolant atmosphere. The pressure tube surrounding the fuel channel split because of overheating and bowing of the burning fuel assembly, and the carbon dioxide coolant leaked out of the reactor.<ref>[http://www.nucleartourist.com/events/part-melt.htm Description of events], Nuclear tourist</ref><ref>[http://canteach.candu.org/library/D407_scr1.pdf Heavy water reactors: Status and projected development] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070413144843/http://canteach.candu.org/library/D407_scr1.pdf |date=13 April 2007 }}, IAEA, 2002</ref>
No [[irradiation]] of workers or the population occurred, though the cavern containing the reactor was seriously contaminated. The cavern was decontaminated and the reactor dismantled over the next few years. The plant was totally decommissioned in 1988 and the last radioactive waste was removed in 2003.<ref>{{cite paper|title=On-site disposal as a decommissioning strategy|url=http://www-pub.iaea.org/MTCD/publications/PDF/te_1124_prn.pdf|publisher=International Atomic Energy Agency|accessdate=6 January 2013|page=67|date=November 1999}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/switzerland-s-first-nuclear-plant-decommissioned/3518582|title=Switzerland’s first nuclear plant decommissioned|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=SWI swissinfo.ch|access-date=2016-10-11|via=}}</ref>
