The '''mina''' (also '''mĕnē''', [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]; {{Lang-he-n|מנה}}){{efn|In the Hebrew tradition, a ''maneh'' had always the weight of 100 silver [[denarii]].}} is an ancient [[Near East]]ern unit of weight, which was divided into 50 [[shekels]]. The mina, like the shekel, was also a unit of [[currency]]. In [[ancient Greece]], it originally equalled 70 [[drachmae]] and later was increased to 100 drachmae.<ref>[[Aristotle]] (unknown date). ''[[Constitution of the Athenians (Aristotle)|Constitution of the Athenians]]'', 10.2.</ref> The Greek word ''mna'' ({{lang|grc|μνᾶ}}) was borrowed from Semitic; compare Hebrew ''māneh'', Aramaic ''mĕnē'', Syriac ''manyā'', Ugaritic ''mn'', and Akkadian ''manū''. However, before it was used as currency, a mina was a unit of measurement, equal to {{convert|1.25|lb|kg}}.
From earliest [[History of Sumer|Sumerian]] times, a mina was a unit of weight. At first, talents and shekels had not yet been introduced. By the time of [[Ur-Nammu]], the mina had a value of 1/60 [[Talent (weight)|talents]] as well as 60 [[shekel]]s. The value of the mina is calculated at {{convert|1.25|lb|kg}}<ref>Edwards, Tom. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121034333/http://www.spiritrestoration.org/Church/Research%20History%20and%20Great%20Links/Biblical%20Weights%20Measure%20and%20Monetary%20System.htm |date=21 January 2012 |title="Bible Weights, Measures, and Monetary Values", ''SpiritRestoration.org''}}. Calculation of weight by number of shekels.</ref><ref>{{Cite Jewish Encyclopedia |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=726&letter=M#2473 |title=Money}}</ref>.
Evidence from [[Ugarit]] indicates that a mina was equivalent to fifty shekels.<ref>Tenney, Merril ed., ''The Zondervan Pictorial Encyclopedia of the Bible'', vol. 5, "Weights and Measures," Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan, 1976.</ref> The prophet [[Ezekiel]] refers to a mina ('maneh' in the King James Version) as sixty shekels, in the [[Book of Ezekiel]] 45:12. [[Jesus of Nazareth]] tells the "[[parable of the minas]]" in [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]] 19:11-27.
From the [[Akkadian Empire|Akkad]]ian period, 2 mina was equal to 1 ''sila'' of water (cf. [[water clock|clepsydra]], water clock).
== Purchasing power == * The price for a slave in Plautus' ''[[Pseudolus]]'' (191 BCE) was 20 minæ; one mina being, according to the commentator, "about $18.05 is USD, or £3 14s. 4d."{{When|date=September 2018}}<ref>{{Perseus|Pl.|Ps.|1.3}}</ref> * In the first century AD [in Greece?], it amounted to about a fourth of the wages earned annually by an agricultural worker. {{cn|date=March 2015}}
